<subSubSection id="93EA76CB97E4FF32FF25F958FDA1B8C5" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E4FF32FF25F958FDA1B8C5" blockId="179.[151,1437,1641,2026]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E4FF32FF25F958FEBFB9C1" bold="true" box="[199,321,1749,1774]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The male abdominal apex of the new species with a pair of tooth-like projections from ninth abdominal tergite as well as the shape of the subgenital plate is similar to the situation in 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E4FF32FB48F977FAB2B83E" authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1888" box="[1194,1356,1785,1809]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugosifrons">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E4FF32FB48F977FAB2B83E" box="[1194,1356,1785,1809]" italics="true" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">E. rugosifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<typeStatus id="044B9BE297E4FF32FABCF977FA62B83D" box="[1374,1436,1786,1810]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">typus</typeStatus>
generis) as described and figured in 
<bibRefCitation id="BF6158B197E4FF32FDC9F893FD2CB819" author="Karny, H. H." box="[555,722,1822,1846]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" pagination="35 - 186" refId="ref187759" refString="Karny, H. H. (1929 a) Revisionen der Gryllacriden des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien einschliesslich der Collection Brunner V. Wattenwyl, 1. Halfte. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien, 43, 35 - 186, Taf. 4 - 6." type="journal article" year="1929">Karny (1929a)</bibRefCitation>
; it differs by the membranous zone between the projections that is absent in the latter species; moreover the head is less wide and the face less rugose than in 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E4FF32FB31F8CFFA8AB876" authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1888" box="[1235,1396,1857,1881]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugosifrons">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E4FF32FB31F8CFFA8AB876" box="[1235,1396,1857,1881]" italics="true" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">E. rugosifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E4FF32FF75F8EBFDE8B851" authority="Griffini (1913 a)" authorityName="Griffini" authorityYear="1913" box="[151,534,1893,1918]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oberthuri">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E4FF32FF75F8EBFEA2B852" box="[151,348,1893,1917]" italics="true" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">Eremus oberthuri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="BF6158B197E4FF32FE81F8E8FDE8B851" author="Griffini, A." box="[355,534,1893,1918]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" pagination="217 - 246" refId="ref186363" refString="Griffini, A. (1913 a) Note sopra Grillacridi australiani, indo-malesi ed etiopici [del Museum d' Histoire naturelle di Parigi]. Atti della Societa Italiana di Scienze Naturali, 51, 217 - 246." type="journal article" year="1913">Griffini (1913a)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
the male subgenital plate is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E4FF32FBF4F8EBFB4BB852" authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1888" box="[1046,1205,1893,1917]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rugosifrons">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E4FF32FBF4F8EBFB4BB852" box="[1046,1205,1893,1917]" italics="true" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">E. rugosifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the new species but the apical projections of the ninth abdominal tergite are missing. 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E4FF32FC41F807FB3DB88D" authority="(Walker, 1869)" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1869" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[931,1219,1929,1954]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Neanias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E4FF32FC41F807FBECB88E" box="[931,1042,1929,1953]" italics="true" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">E. basalis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="BF6158B197E4FF32FBC0F804FB44B88D" author="Walker, F." box="[1058,1210,1929,1954]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" refId="ref189674" refString="Walker, F. (1869) Catalogue of the Specimens of Dermaptera Saltatoria and Supplement to the Blattariae in the Collection of the British Museum. Pt 1. [iv +] 1 - 224; London (British Museum of Natural History)." type="book" year="1869">Walker, 1869</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E4FF32FB19F807FECFB8E9" authority="Bolivar, 1900" authorityName="Bolivar" authorityYear="1900" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegantulus">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E4FF32FB19F807FA62B88E" box="[1275,1436,1929,1953]" italics="true" pageId="179" pageNumber="180">E. elegantulus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="BF6158B197E4FF32FF75F820FECFB8E9" author="Bolivar, I." box="[151,305,1965,1990]" pageId="179" pageNumber="180" pagination="761 - 812" refId="ref184407" refString="Bolivar, I. (1900) Les Orthopteres de St-Joseph's College a Trichinopoly (Sud de l' Inde). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, 68 [1899], 761 - 812, pls 11 - 12; Paris." type="journal article" year="1900">Bolívar, 1900</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
have the apical margin of the subgenital plate projecting between the bases of the styli while in the new species it is concavely emarginated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="93EA76CB97E3FF35FF25FF1AFEADBB78" pageId="180" pageNumber="181" type="description">
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E3FF35FF25FF1AFF17BE6F" blockId="180.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="180" pageNumber="181">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E3FF35FF25FF1AFEA7BF9F" bold="true" box="[199,345,151,176]" pageId="180" pageNumber="181">Description.</emphasis>
Small to medium sized species (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E3FF35FD1AFF1AFCA0BF9F" box="[760,862,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 60" captionStartId="174.[151,250,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[191,1378,193,1645]" captionTargetId="figure@174.[191,1378,193,1645]" captionTargetPageId="174" captionText="FIGURE 60. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–E, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (C–D) and female (E); F–G, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; H, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; I–J, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female type BrW17.124.—Lateral view (A, C, E–F, H–I), dorsal view (B, D, G, J). Scale 10 mm (Brunner's types not to scale)." pageId="180" pageNumber="181">Figs. 60</figureCitation>
A–B). Head: Face ovoid; nearly smooth, finely shagreened; fastigium verticis distinctly wider than scapus; ocelli indistinct; fastigium frontis separated from fastigium verticis by a fine suture; subocular furrows distinct, widening ventrad to a wide depression (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E3FF35FAC4FF52FA71BFD7" box="[1318,1423,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="180" pageNumber="181">Fig. 61A</figureCitation>
). Abdominal tergites two and three each with two rows of very small stridulatory pegs (3, 3–5; 5–6, 4–5; n = 
<specimenCount id="CDF6EEC997E3FF35FA6CFE89FF23BE6F" pageId="180" pageNumber="181" type="male">2 males</specimenCount>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E3FF35FF25FEC1FBA9BE4B" blockId="180.[151,1437,151,1184]" box="[199,1111,332,357]" pageId="180" pageNumber="181">Wings reduced to minute pads not reaching hind margin of corresponding notum.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E3FF35FF25FEFDFCD7BD37" blockId="180.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="180" pageNumber="181">Legs: Fore coxa with a spine at fore margin; fore and mid femora unarmed; fore tibiae with 4, mid tibiae with only 3 pairs of ventral spines (in one male first pair completely lacking, in the other male there is a minute spine on external side, on the right legs on both sides) and 1 pair of very small ventral spurs; hind femur with 4–6 external and 3–7 internal spines on ventral margins; hind tibia with spaced spines on both dorsal margins, ventral margins without pre-apical spine; with 3 apical spurs on both sides.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E3FF35FF25FDA9FBC0BD87" blockId="180.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="180" pageNumber="181">Coloration. General color intense dark yellow with black marks; vertex black; pronotum yellow with black rim; legs brownish red with coxa, trochanter and genicular area black; thoracic sternites black; abdominal sternites yellow with black margins except for hind margin which is yellow. Face black with an oval yellow spot on fastigium frontis; clypeus and labrum dark brownish red, margin of clypeus yellow.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E3FF35FF25FD39FED1BCC2" blockId="180.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="180" pageNumber="181">
Male. Eighth abdominal tergite black; prolonged and towards end globular. Ninth abdominal tergite black, together with preceding segment globular; apical margin in middle bent proximad and split forming a small ovoid membranous zone; apex on both sides of midline with a short acute tooth (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E3FF35FBEBFD71FB8DBC3A" box="[1033,1139,764,789]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="180" pageNumber="181">Fig. 61B</figureCitation>
). Tenth abdominal tergite forming a short black band; sub-interrupted in middle by small epiproct. Epiproct semicircular, in middle with a strongly sclerotised groove with a deeper pit at tip; paraproctes forming large black plates mediad of bases of cerci, and meeting in midline. Eight sternite shorter but wider than preceding sternites with lateral margins up-bent; subgenital plate wider than long, little vaulted in basal area, afterwards little depressed except at both lateral margins, apical margin concave; styli very small, inserted at little projecting lateral angles (
<figureCitation id="43CB39C597E3FF35FB2AFC22FACCBCE7" box="[1224,1330,943,968]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="175.[151,250,1779,1801]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1758]" captionTargetId="figure@175.[149,1438,193,1758]" captionTargetPageId="175" captionText="FIGURE 61. Genus Eremus: A–B, E. tigris sp. nov. male paratype (A) and holotype (B); C–D, E. nigrifrons Brunner, 1888 female type; E, E. sp. male (&quot;Eremus nigrifrons Br. =? basalis Walker&quot; det. Karny); F, E. b. basalis (Walker, 1869) female holotype; G–K, E. geniculatus Brunner, 1888 female paratype (G–H), female holotype (I) and male paratype (J–K); L–N, E. r. rugosifrons Brunner, 1888 male type BrW9787 (L–M) and female (N).—Face (A, C, G, L), male abdominal apex in ventroapical view (B, E, K, M), end of female abdomen with seventh sternite, subgenital plate and base of ovipositor (D, F, H–I, N), habitus lateral view (J)." pageId="180" pageNumber="181">Fig. 61B</figureCitation>
). Phallus membranous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E3FF35FF25FC7AFE6EBB3F" blockId="180.[151,1437,151,1184]" box="[199,400,1015,1040]" pageId="180" pageNumber="181">Female unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E3FF35FF25FB90FEADBB78" blockId="180.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="180" pageNumber="181">
