<subSubSection id="93EA76CB97E3FF35FF25FBE9FEEDBB8F" pageId="180" pageNumber="181" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="DB4F254097E3FF35FF25FBE9FEEDBB8F" blockId="180.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="180" pageNumber="181">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E3FF35FF25FBE9FEB0BB52" bold="true" box="[199,334,1124,1149]" pageId="180" pageNumber="181">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the new species refers to the striped abdomen; from Latin 
<taxonomicName id="1CF05EC397E3FF35FB57FBE8FB0EBB53" authorityName="Ingrisch" authorityYear="2018" box="[1205,1264,1125,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllacrididae" genus="Eremus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="180" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigris">
<emphasis id="E984F95297E3FF35FB57FBE8FB0EBB53" box="[1205,1264,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="180" pageNumber="181">tigris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tiger; noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
